{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3f979a8f-7959-4fa3-970b-e414ff7e78cf","content":"The project doesn't exist yet in this directory, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a `dotnet tool`:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key properties explained\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the package as a global/local dotnet tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `PackageId` | The name on NuGet.org |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- Include a `README.md` in the package via `<None Include=\"README.md\" Pack=\"true\" PackagePath=\"/\" />`.\n- Get your API key from [nuget.org/account/apikeys](https://www.nuget.org/account/apikeys).\n- Since it's stdio-based MCP, no additional transport config is needed — the tool just reads stdin/writes stdout.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fc2ac976-e6bd-49a6-bcdf-183e34d60db0","outputTokens":575,"requestId":"5C50:D447C:1D3EEB5:20634BC:69FA941A"},"id":"a40362dd-f8e8-4250-a6bf-